%description:
Linux-parity PSH-on-write-boundary (pushSegmentsOnWriteBoundary). Linux
sets the PSH flag on the segment carrying the last byte of a write once the
send buffer drains past it; INET does not by default. This test reuses
tcp_nagle_3.test's exact scenario (same sendScript) with the option ON, and
pins that PSH now appears on the segments that carry the final byte of each
write burst.

Two write bursts land as single segments here: the 100B tail write (2.0005)
becomes segment 8073:8101, and it -- carrying the last buffered byte, with an
empty queue behind it -- gains PSH. The larger writes coalesce/segment into
multiple MSS-sized segments; only the one carrying the write's final byte
(with nothing more queued at that instant) gets PSH.

Falsification: tcp_nagle_3.test is the exact same scenario with the option
OFF (its default) -- its pinned trace shows NO PSH on any of these segments.
This test's %contains lines below would all fail against that default trace,
so the pair is a direct on/off falsification of the feature.

%inifile: omnetpp.ini
[General]
record-vector-results = false
ned-path = .;../../../../src;../../lib

cmdenv-event-banners=false
cmdenv-express-mode=false

*.testing=true

*.tcptester.cmdenv-log-level=DEBUG
*.*_app.cmdenv-log-level=DEBUG
**.cmdenv-log-level=OFF

*.cli_app.sendScript="1.00 3000; 1.0005 2000; 2.00 3000; 2.0005 100"

*.*_tcp.pushSegmentsOnWriteBoundary = true

include ../../lib/defaults.ini

%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The 100B tail write becomes one segment carrying the connection's final buffered
%# byte with an empty queue behind it -> PSH set (shown as "P" in the tcpdump line).
%contains: stdout
[2.205 A011] A.1000 > B.2000: A P 8073:8101(28) ack 501 win 16384
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%# The first write's tail segment (4097:5001, the byte-3000 boundary of write #1
%# once write #2's bytes have not yet been Nagle-released) carries PSH too.
%contains: stdout
[1.413 A007] A.1000 > B.2000: A P 4097:5001(904) ack 501 win 16384
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
%postrun-command: grep "undisposed object:" test.out > test_undisposed.out || true
%not-contains: test_undisposed.out
undisposed object: (
%#--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
